Hey R,

This situation is definitely distressing, and I get you. Know that you are not alone and that God is with you. I will pray for you.

I noticed a few things about how you are thinking about God and your situation with homosexual thoughts and desires.

Firstly, you mentioned having to live up to expectations/image of being a Christian and also having to follow a lot of rules that are too much to bear. You are absolutely right that it would be too much to bear to live up to this perfect image - this is exactly why people struggled so much before Jesus Christ came and died on the cross for us - they were trying to reach the standard of God and failing miserably. As a follower of Christ, we don't need to stand on our works and our own goodness, we stand on the finished work and sacrifice of Jesus Christ. It is his perfect life, his sacrificial death and resurrection that allows us to draw near to Him. So know that, no matter how low you are feeling, that God is there for you, that he loves you, and he wants only good for you. And that you can always call on him even when it feels like you can't or don't deserve it. This is actually the key to overcoming sin - drawing closer and closer to God, filling up that hole of emptiness inside us with Him rather than with our fleshly desires or sins. 

We think that sins and (even non-sinful, good) desires will satisfy us, but ultimately don't, because we have a built-in need for God in our lives to be truly joyful, fulfilled and peaceful. The Bible also says a lot about how sin works. While sin may make you feel good temporarily, it actually hurts our spirit and it is not what our spirit wants. Sin ultimately leads to death when it grows to its full extent in our lives. Because sin is like that, sin gets you to do more of it over time, to think more about it, until it takes over. This applies to any sort of sin, whether sexual, violent, prideful sin etc.
Thankfully God's love and presence is stronger and victorious over sin. God's love can grow in you, it can change you and change your desires into spiritual desires.
The reason why I mention this, is so that you know that while it can seem like you only want sin while you are in it, that isn't and doesn't have to be the case. Sin wants to grow and take over lives. It seems like the desire for that thing is who you are and what you want, but actually your spirit does not want sin, and it is not who you are. Your desires can and will change when you trust in God and rely on God to change you, and you will find yourself wanting more and more of God rather than sin or other desires. You will also find, that your identity will change towards your true identity - remember our identity is in Christ and who He created us to be, not in things we like or even some of the ways we and others think of our selves. These changes may seem impossible to you right now, but nothing is impossible for God.

We must be aware that when we turn and repent from sin (which is to transform ourselves away from sin and towards God), that this is a spiritual war we are waging. We fight not against flesh and blood, but against powers and principalities. This means that we are not fighting with people or ourselves, but actually there are spiritual forces that are encouraging us to sin and deceiving us with incorrect beliefs. Those thoughts that make us want to sin, that tell us things about ourselves and make us feel horrible, they CAN come from unclean/evil spirits. However overtime these thoughts can become a pattern in our minds and lives, at that point they become a stronghold (a strong thing, which could be thought pattern, or a strong desire or a strong identity) that we need to tear down. 
The weapons of spiritual war are: prayer, reading the word of God, and fasting. Also waiting for the lord (thinking about God and waiting for God's reply after we pray) and gathering with others (going to church and sharing your spiritual walk with other trusted Christians). I have found these tools very effective, you should apply them to your life and see what changes it brings. 

The second thing that I noticed, was that it seems that you have a lot of fear and anxiety around the topic of homosexuality. Remember that Jesus has already lived a perfect life, taken on your sin and paid the price for your sin, if you believe and trust in Him. There is no condemnation for those that are in Christ. This means that when we trust in Jesus, our sins have been dealt with - so God doesn't condemn us for our sins. We don't need to feel condemned by sin, as condemnation - thoughts like you aren't good enough, you are horrible/disgusting/pathetic, God won't listen to you - these type of thoughts DO NOT come from God, but from evil sources - again this is spiritual warfare, a spiritual attack. When we sin, often evil takes the opportunity to create a wedge between us and God by speaking evil into our minds.
Ask God for his forgiveness, and trust in the done work of Christ and His love for you, as it has allowed us to draw near Him even when we have sinned. However, I will say that this is not an open invitation for us to sin willingly because we think we will be forgiven, for that makes the sin more serious (a presumptuous sin). It should be the opposite. God's love and forgiveness, which we don't deserve, makes us want to become better. 

Just now when I addressed anxiety and fear, I was talking about the fear of punishment, in case that was the thing that was making you scared. However when I read your post, I noticed that you were often trying to avoid hearing about homosexuality when it was negative. This sounds like a stronghold and spiritual warfare for your identity. As you have had these desires for a few years, and you say to yourself that your interests have all become based around homosexual things, it sounds like you have made homosexuality a bit of a stronghold in your life. Strongholds can be connected to spirits, though they don't have to be, and they try to protect themselves (like a castle or a walled city). This is probably why you react that way when you come across something that threatens those ideas and desires. You might be feeling emotional because you feel like you and your identity is being attacked. Remember again, our identity is in Christ, not in what we want or like - those things can change, but God is unchanging. I would pray to God for help to tear down strongholds because He can do it - the Bible says the weaker we are in a situation, the stronger He is to help us. It is difficult, but hold onto God when you feel the fear, and trust in Him while you face these things and let go of these desires, fears, and identities. Remember he wants good things for you and your life, it is when we trust in Him and follow Him, that we can be transformed to receive these better things in our lives and the eternal things of the spirit. 
We can only turn away from something if we turn to something else. Turn to the things of God.

Ask and seek God truly, and He will reveal the truth to you, as well as what you need. You don't need to take my word for it, nor other people's words. It's a good sign that you are willing to acknowledge that you and God may not be aligned in some areas - that's a great step towards seeking him truly. We have to be humble and willing to be taught, this is when God talks to you. When your heart is in the right place. If you are only willing to hear Him say or do something the way you want it to be, he will be distant from you.
